  <!-- ===================================================================
       SECTION 5: SOCIAL SCIENCE APPLICATIONS
       =================================================================== -->
  <section id="social-science">
    <h2>Social Science Applications</h2>
    <p>
      The tools covered in this module: alignment, prompting,
      reasoning, evaluation: are already transforming social science
      methodology. This section highlights key papers that demonstrate how
      these techniques open new research possibilities and introduce new
      methodological challenges.
    </p>

    <h3>Alignment &amp; Opinion Representation</h3>
    <p>
      Post-training does not just affect model style: it shapes what
      perspectives models represent. Understanding this is essential for any
      research that uses model outputs as data.
    </p>

    <div class="course-note">
      <svg class="course-note__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/><path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/>
      </svg>
      <p>
        <strong>Santurkar et al. (2023),</strong>
        <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.17548" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Whose Opinions Do Language Models Reflect?</em></a>
        ICML. Demonstrates that RLHF shifts model outputs toward the opinion
        distributions of specific demographic groups: particularly
        those overrepresented among annotators. For social scientists using
        LLMs to simulate human responses or measure public opinion, this
        finding is critical: the model&rsquo;s &ldquo;opinions&rdquo; are
        partly an artifact of whose preferences shaped its training.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>Prompting as Experimental Design</h3>
    <p>
      The prompting techniques covered in this module are not just practical
      tools: they are methodological choices with direct implications
      for research validity.
    </p>

    <div class="course-note">
      <svg class="course-note__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/><path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/>
      </svg>
      <p>
        <strong>Ziems et al. (2024),</strong>
        <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.03514" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Can Large Language Models Transform Computational Social Science?</em></a>
        Computational Linguistics. A comprehensive review of LLM applications
        across computational social science that treats prompt design as
        experimental design. The paper emphasises that methodological validity
        in CSS requires the same attention to instrument design that
        traditional social science demands: and that LLMs introduce new
        validity concerns (prompt sensitivity, model opacity, temporal
        instability) alongside their capabilities.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="course-note">
      <svg class="course-note__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/><path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/>
      </svg>
      <p>
        <strong>Argyle et al. (2023),</strong>
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/pan.2023.2" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Out of One, Many: Using Language Models to Simulate Human Samples.</em></a>
        Political Analysis. Demonstrates that prompt framing: how you
        specify a persona&rsquo;s demographic characteristics, backstory, and
        context: substantially determines the distribution of simulated
        survey responses. Under carefully controlled prompting, LLMs can
        approximate some population-level patterns, but the prompt is doing
        much of the work. This connects the prompting techniques from this
        module directly to the question of whether LLM outputs can stand in
        for human data.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>Reasoning &amp; Analytical Complexity</h3>

    <div class="course-note">
      <svg class="course-note__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/><path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/>
      </svg>
      <p>
        <strong>Huang &amp; Chang (2023),</strong>
        <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.10403" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Towards Reasoning in Large Language Models: A Survey.</em></a>
        Findings of ACL. Surveys the reasoning capabilities and limitations of
        large language models. For social science applications, the key finding
        is that chain-of-thought prompting can improve performance on nuanced
        text annotation tasks: detecting implicit sentiment, sarcasm, or
        framing in political text: where direct classification tends to
        miss subtlety. However, the survey also cautions that model-generated
        reasoning is not always faithful to the model&rsquo;s actual
        computation; the &ldquo;explanation&rdquo; may be a post-hoc
        rationalisation rather than a transparent reasoning trace.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>Evaluation as Research Design</h3>

    <div class="course-note">
      <svg class="course-note__icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M2 3h6a4 4 0 0 1 4 4v14a3 3 0 0 0-3-3H2z"/><path d="M22 3h-6a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v14a3 3 0 0 1 3-3h7z"/>
      </svg>
      <p>
        <strong>Weber &amp; Reichardt (2023),</strong>
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2310.07499" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Evaluation is All You Need.</em></a>
        Offers a framework for thinking about LLM evaluation in social science
        contexts. The central argument: benchmark thinking translates directly
        to research design. Just as you would not trust a survey instrument
        without validating it, you should not trust an LLM classifier without
        building a task-specific evaluation. The paper provides practical
        guidance on constructing domain-specific evaluations before committing
        to a model.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="key-takeaway">
      <p class="key-takeaway__label">Key Takeaway</p>
      <p>
        The foundations covered in this module: post-training,
        prompting, reasoning, and evaluation: are not just technical
        prerequisites. They are <strong>methodological decisions</strong>
        that directly affect research validity. Alignment shapes what
        perspectives models represent. Prompt design defines your construct.
        Reasoning techniques trade cost for accuracy. Evaluation practices
        determine whether your results are trustworthy. The subsequent modules
        build directly on these tools: Day 3 covers classification pipelines
        at scale, validation frameworks, and the decision of when to fine-tune
        instead of prompt.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</CourseLayout>

<script is:inline>
(function() {
  var explorer = document.getElementById("prompt-explorer");
  var content = document.getElementById("prompt-explorer-content");
  var insight = document.getElementById("prompt-explorer-insight");
  if (!explorer || !content) return;

  var strategies = [
    {
      parts: [
        { type: "system", label: "System", text: "You are a political text analysis assistant." },
        { type: "user", label: "User", text: "Does the author of the following tweet support or oppose the Women's March?\nAnswer with one word: support or oppose.\n\nTweet: Great job marching today everyone, really changed the world. \ud83d\ude44\nAnswer:" },
        { type: "assistant", label: "Assistant", text: "support" }
      ],
      insight: "Zero-shot: only the task description is provided. The model relies on its training to interpret the task. Simple and cheap, but may miss sarcasm or apply inconsistent criteria. Here it misreads the sarcastic tone as genuine support."
    },
    {
      parts: [
        { type: "system", label: "System", text: "You are a political text analysis assistant." },
        { type: "user", label: "User", text: "Does the author of each tweet support or oppose the Women's March?\nAnswer with one word: support or oppose.\n\nTweet: So proud of everyone who showed up today! #WomensMarch\nAnswer: support\n\nTweet: These protesters need to get a real job.\nAnswer: oppose\n\nTweet: Standing with my sisters. This is what democracy looks like.\nAnswer: support\n\nTweet: Great job marching today everyone, really changed the world. \ud83d\ude44\nAnswer:" },
        { type: "assistant", label: "Assistant", text: "oppose" }
      ],
      insight: "Few-shot: labeled examples anchor the model\u2019s understanding. The examples define the classification pattern implicitly. More tokens per request, but the model learns the intended criteria from the demonstrations and correctly identifies the sarcasm."
    },
    {
      parts: [
        { type: "system", label: "System", text: "You are a political text analysis assistant." },
        { type: "user", label: "User", text: "Read the following tweet about the Women's March. First, explain in\none sentence what the author's position seems to be. Then, on a new\nline, classify the tweet as: support or oppose.\n\nTweet: Great job marching today everyone, really changed the world. \ud83d\ude44" },
        { type: "reasoning", label: "Assistant", text: "The author uses sarcastic language (\"really changed the world\" paired\nwith an eye-roll emoji) to mock the march, indicating disapproval.\n\noppose" }
      ],
      insight: "Chain-of-thought: the model reasons before classifying. The explicit reasoning step catches sarcasm by analysing the mismatch between literal text and the emoji. More expensive, but produces an auditable rationale and handles ambiguous cases better."
    }
  ];

  var currentPanel = 0;

  function render() {
    var s = strategies[currentPanel];
    var html = "";
    for (var i = 0; i < s.parts.length; i++) {
      var p = s.parts[i];
      var borderColor, bgColor, labelColor;
      if (p.type === "system") {
        borderColor = "var(--border, #E2E6EE)";
        bgColor = "var(--surface, #F2F4F8)";
        labelColor = "var(--text-muted, #6B7280)";
      } else if (p.type === "user") {
        borderColor = "var(--accent, #2D8ABF)";
        bgColor = "var(--blue-9, #E6F0FA)";
        labelColor = "var(--accent-dark, #1E5A8A)";
      } else {
        borderColor = "var(--accent, #2D8ABF)";
        bgColor = "var(--accent-bg, #F0F7FF)";
        labelColor = "var(--accent, #2D8ABF)";
      }
      html += '<div style="margin-bottom:0.5rem;padding:0.6rem 0.8rem;border-left:3px solid ' + borderColor + ';background:' + bgColor + ';border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">';
      html += '<div style="font-weight:600;font-size:0.78rem;color:' + labelColor + ';margin-bottom:0.25rem;font-family:var(--font-body,sans-serif);">' + p.label + '</div>';
      html += '<div style="color:var(--text-sec,#3D4455);font-size:0.8rem;line-height:1.5;white-space:pre-wrap;">' + p.text + '</div>';
      html += '</div>';
    }
    content.innerHTML = html;
    insight.textContent = s.insight;
  }

  var btns = explorer.querySelectorAll(".attention-explorer__sentence-btn");
  btns.forEach(function(btn, i) {
    btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
      btns.forEach(function(b, j) {
        b.classList.toggle("attention-explorer__sentence-btn--active", j === i);
      });
      currentPanel = i;
      render();
    });
  });

  render();
})();
</script>

<script is:inline>
(function() {
  var svg = document.getElementById("model-landscape-svg");
  var insight = document.getElementById("model-landscape-insight");
  var explorer = document.getElementById("model-explorer");
  if (!svg || !explorer) return;

  var models = [
    { name: "GPT-4o", cap: 0.87, cost: 0.62, type: "closed" },
    { name: "Claude 3.5 Sonnet", cap: 0.88, cost: 0.55, type: "closed" },
    { name: "Gemini 1.5 Pro", cap: 0.84, cost: 0.50, type: "closed" },
    { name: "GPT-4o mini", cap: 0.73, cost: 0.12, type: "closed" },
    { name: "o1", cap: 0.95, cost: 0.92, type: "closed" },
    { name: "DeepSeek-V3", cap: 0.85, cost: 0.10, type: "open" },
    { name: "Llama 3.1 405B", cap: 0.82, cost: 0.42, type: "open" },
    { name: "Llama 3.1 70B", cap: 0.75, cost: 0.18, type: "open" },
    { name: "Qwen 2.5 72B", cap: 0.77, cost: 0.16, type: "open" },
    { name: "Mistral Large", cap: 0.78, cost: 0.35, type: "open" },
    { name: "Llama 3.1 8B", cap: 0.56, cost: 0.04, type: "open" },
    { name: "Gemma 2 27B", cap: 0.67, cost: 0.10, type: "open" }
  ];

  var filter = "all";

  function draw() {
    var pad = 60;
    var w = 520, h = 380;
    var plotL = pad + 10, plotR = w - 30;
    var plotT = 30, plotB = h - pad;
    var plotW = plotR - plotL, plotH = plotB - plotT;
    var s = "";

    s += '<rect x="' + plotL + '" y="' + plotT + '" width="' + plotW + '" height="' + plotH + '" rx="4" style="fill:var(--surface,#F2F4F8);stroke:var(--border,#E2E6EE);"/>';

    for (var g = 0.2; g <= 0.8; g += 0.2) {
      var gy = plotB - g * plotH;
      s += '<line x1="' + plotL + '" y1="' + gy + '" x2="' + plotR + '" y2="' + gy + '" style="stroke:var(--border-lt,#EAEEF4);" stroke-width="0.5"/>';
      var gx = plotL + g * plotW;
      s += '<line x1="' + gx + '" y1="' + plotT + '" x2="' + gx + '" y2="' + plotB + '" style="stroke:var(--border-lt,#EAEEF4);" stroke-width="0.5"/>';
    }

    s += '<text x="' + (plotL + plotW / 2) + '" y="' + (h - 8) + '" text-anchor="middle" style="fill:var(--text-muted,#6B7280);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="11" font-weight="600">Relative Cost (low \u2192 high)</text>';
    s += '<text x="14" y="' + (plotT + plotH / 2) + '" text-anchor="middle" style="fill:var(--text-muted,#6B7280);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="11" font-weight="600" transform="rotate(-90,14,' + (plotT + plotH / 2) + ')">Approximate Capability \u2192</text>';
    s += '<text x="' + plotL + '" y="' + (plotB + 16) + '" text-anchor="middle" style="fill:var(--text-muted,#6B7280);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="9">Low</text>';
    s += '<text x="' + plotR + '" y="' + (plotB + 16) + '" text-anchor="middle" style="fill:var(--text-muted,#6B7280);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="9">High</text>';

    s += '<circle cx="' + (plotR - 95) + '" cy="' + (plotT - 24) + '" r="5" style="fill:var(--accent,#2D8ABF);" opacity="0.85"/>';
    s += '<text x="' + (plotR - 85) + '" y="' + (plotT - 20) + '" style="fill:var(--text-sec,#3D4455);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="9">Closed-weight</text>';
    s += '<circle cx="' + (plotR - 95) + '" cy="' + (plotT - 12) + '" r="5" style="fill:var(--accent-dark,#1E5A8A);" opacity="0.85"/>';
    s += '<text x="' + (plotR - 85) + '" y="' + (plotT - 8) + '" style="fill:var(--text-sec,#3D4455);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="9">Open-weight</text>';

    var filtered = models.filter(function(m) {
      if (filter === "all") return true;
      return m.type === filter;
    });

    // Pareto frontier: models not dominated on cost-capability
    var frontier = filtered.slice().sort(function(a, b) { return a.cost - b.cost; });
    var paretoPoints = [];
    var bestCap = -1;
    for (var fi = 0; fi < frontier.length; fi++) {
      if (frontier[fi].cap > bestCap) {
        bestCap = frontier[fi].cap;
        paretoPoints.push(frontier[fi]);
      }
    }
    if (paretoPoints.length > 1) {
      var fp = "";
      for (var pi = 0; pi < paretoPoints.length; pi++) {
        var fpx = plotL + paretoPoints[pi].cost * plotW;
        var fpy = plotB - (paretoPoints[pi].cap - 0.4) / 0.6 * plotH;
        fp += (pi === 0 ? "M" : "L") + fpx + "," + fpy;
      }
      s += '<path d="' + fp + '" fill="none" style="stroke:var(--accent,#2D8ABF);" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="6,4" opacity="0.5"/>';
      s += '<text x="' + (plotL + paretoPoints[0].cost * plotW + 4) + '" y="' + (plotB - (paretoPoints[0].cap - 0.4) / 0.6 * plotH + 16) + '" style="fill:var(--text-muted,#6B7280);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="8" font-style="italic">cost-capability frontier</text>';
    }

    var labels = [];
    for (var i = 0; i < filtered.length; i++) {
      var m = filtered[i];
      var px = plotL + m.cost * plotW;
      var py = plotB - (m.cap - 0.4) / 0.6 * plotH;
      var color = m.type === "closed" ? "var(--accent,#2D8ABF)" : "var(--accent-dark,#1E5A8A)";
      s += '<circle cx="' + px + '" cy="' + py + '" r="5.5" style="fill:' + color + ';" opacity="0.85"/>';
      var anchor = m.cost > 0.6 ? "end" : "start";
      var lx = anchor === "start" ? px + 9 : px - 9;
      var ly = py - 8;
      labels.push({ x: lx, y: ly, a: anchor, t: m.name });
    }

    for (var k = 0; k < labels.length; k++) {
      for (var j = 0; j < k; j++) {
        if (Math.abs(labels[k].x - labels[j].x) < 60 && Math.abs(labels[k].y - labels[j].y) < 12) {
          labels[k].y = labels[k].y > labels[j].y ? labels[j].y + 13 : labels[j].y - 13;
        }
      }
    }

    for (var q = 0; q < labels.length; q++) {
      var lb = labels[q];
      s += '<text x="' + lb.x + '" y="' + lb.y + '" text-anchor="' + lb.a + '" style="fill:var(--text-sec,#3D4455);font-family:var(--font-body);" font-size="9">' + lb.t + '</text>';
    }

    svg.innerHTML = s;
  }

  var filterMap = ["all", "open", "closed"];
  var btns = explorer.querySelectorAll(".attention-explorer__sentence-btn");
  btns.forEach(function(btn, i) {
    btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
      btns.forEach(function(b, j) {
        b.classList.toggle("attention-explorer__sentence-btn--active", j === i);
      });
      filter = filterMap[i];
      draw();
      var msgs = [
        "Approximate positions based on public benchmarks and pricing as of early 2025. Capability reflects an approximate composite of MMLU, Arena ELO, and coding benchmarks. The dashed line marks the cost-capability frontier. Verify current data before making decisions.",
        "Open-weight models: weights are publicly available. You can run them locally, inspect them, and guarantee reproducibility. Cost depends on your compute infrastructure. The dashed line marks the cost-capability frontier.",
        "Closed-weight models: accessible only via API. Generally higher capability on the hardest tasks, but costs per token and model versions can change without notice. The dashed line marks the cost-capability frontier."
      ];
      insight.textContent = msgs[i];
    });
  });

  draw();
})();
</script>
